item.title: Janrain Engage: A Preview
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded:
For quite sometime now, I wanted to provide a single sign-in facility for my website so that it helps me connect my site to the social web. While I was looking for various alternatives I found this powerful tool -Janrain Engage (formerly RPX).

What is Janrain Engage

Janrain Engage helps connect your site to the social web through a robust set of APIs and social widget interfaces. Janrain Engage allows your visitors to sign-in to your site with their existing accounts on Facebook, Google, Twitter, Yahoo!, LinkedIn, Windows Live, MySpace, AOL or other networks and then publish their comments, purchases, reviews or other activities from your site to multiple social networks. Ultimately, a Janrain Engage solution accelerates your user registration and sign-in process by quickly and easily converting anonymous site visitors into active registered users. In addition, Janrain Engage enables you to import a rich set of profile data from your users' preferred networks allowing you to gain both deeper insight into your users behavior and keep their profiles up to date.

Feature

  • • Authentication via Facebook, Google, Twitter, Yahoo!, LinkedIn, Windows Live and up to 10 additional social platforms.
  • • Ability to gather rich online user profile data and address books.
  • • Social Publishing.
For details visit: Jainrain's Site
In my next post I will provide a tutorial on how to implement Janrain.

item.title: Interview Paranoia
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded: Got my offer letter from Tata Consultancy Services a couple of days ago. Hopefully will be joining as an Assistant Systems Engineer. Thought I would describe the interview which took place on 13th January. Now TCS usually has two rounds: Aptitude Test and Personal Interview (Technical and HR). Being in the top 5 in our stream, I did not have to sit for the aptitude test and was given a chance to appear for the Personal Interview directly. The cut-off for the aptitude in our college was 33 out of 35 (which is unexpectedly high). I went for the interview and was greeted by a young recruiter from TCS, and then the following took place: Interviewer: So you are Suplab Debnath? Me (with a big smile): Yes Sir Interviewer (glancing through my CV): So where is Durganagar (...its my address)? Me: explained in detail Interviewer (with a smile): You seem very calm. Do you ever get excited? Me: Yes sir, I am calm and I do get excited under certain situations. Interviewer: Do you like sports? Me: Not really sir, I am more of a foodie and I have a knack for cooking. Interviewer: So you like pizzas, burgers? Me (with a smile): No sir, i love home cooked meals more.... Interviewer (also smiling): Like luchi, aloor-dum, .... Me: Yes sir. Interviewer: Are you feeling confident? Me: Yes Sir. Interviewer: Can you tell me the difference between Oracle and MySQL? Me: Tried to point out a few differences...but he didn't seem convinced Interviewer: What is an ER- Diagram? Me: Explained it with confidence. Interviewer: Can you draw the ER diagram for a Library Management System. Me: Did so... Interviewer: (Pointed out a few details) what will happen if i remove this (and that)? Me: Tried to explain (atleast as much as I knew) Interviewer: Implement 5NF in a table? Me: Defined 5NF, because honestly I didn't know how to to it Interviewer (not impressed): What is DKNF? Me: Explained Interviewer: You are the onlyson of your parents? Me: Yes Sir Interviewer: What if you are not selected? Me (seriously): Sir I have the right aptitude for this job, and have the technical know-how. I am confident you will select me. Next He starts asking me a few weird questions from C and Datastructure, most of which I fail to answer. :( Interviewer (with a smile): Still Confident? Me: Yes Sir Interviewer: What is an AVL tree? Me: (explained) Interviewer (draws a tree on a sheet of paper): Is this an AVL tree? Me: No sir, we have to balance it to form an AVL tree Interviewer: Then balance it Me: (tried to but not perfect :P) Next He asked me a few questions from Java, and I nailed it. :D Interviewer: Do you have any questions? Me: Sir since I have done my summer training in PHP, is there any scope of my utilising it in TCS? Interviewer: We do have a few areas where we do implement it, but be ready to learn new things. Me: (assured him that I am always willing to try out new technologies) Interviewer: Any other questions? Me: No sir Interviewer: Alright that will be all you may leave I got up shook his hand and left :) That was my first interview experience!!!!

item.title: Nothing Can Be As Crazy... - A Review
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded:
Off the things which I do regularly in my life, visiting the book fair is one of them. This year I picked up a copy of "Nothing Can Be As Crazy" by Ajay Mohan Jain, hoping it would be a wonderful read. And honestly after finishing the book last night, I realized it has become one of my favorites. The author, Ajay Mohan Jain is an alumunus of IIT Kanpur and trained at IIM Ahmedabad, who has worked for a leading commercial bank for many years.
Nothing can be as Crazy... is the story of a typical service-class Indian, Suresh, who works in a bank. He is naive and conservative, and finds himself out of sync at every stage of life. Being a second-generation city migrant, he has not yet acquired the urban garb completely, and still finds certain things beyond his perception.
The novel is set mainly in the cities of Hyderabad and Calcutta(now Kolkata) and Uttar Pradesh. The main protagonist of the novel is Suresh, an ex-IIT"ian, who is an introvert by nature. Although the "never-say-die" attitude of suresh is commendable. Unlike other novels, this one is more like a collection of past experiences, instead of a long piece of story. The book manages to capture almost all faecets of life, from the first job experiences, the typical bull-sessions with friends, the first experiences of boozing and women, to the seriousness of family life. The reader finds himself/herself maturing with each page he/she turns. Towards the beginning of the book we see life with curiousity, having fun with friends, trying out new things and enjoying the state of being employed. But with each passing chapter we find that life is a weird mesh of events which teaches us one lesson after another, until finally we learn to accept life and its crazy ways. The author also provides a detailed description about the inner sanctums of work-life and the way in which it is filled with corruption and fake attitutudes of people. In short it is a wonderful book to read, teaching us the crazy ways of life and helping us remember our past crazy days... :) Sources: www.ajaymohanjain.com Shared by the author himself on facebook:

item.title: Inception- Live
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded: Thank you very much Mr. Christopher Nolan, for that wonderful movie of yours. Yeah, I'm referring to "Inception" (you know, the one about dream theft :P ). Well anyways, this is not a review about the movie, nor am I planning to write one. This is more like a story (atleast that's what I would like to call it), with its place and characters all real, atleast as real as it can be. Anyways thought I would write about it.... The events of this story started last night at 8pm, when I decided to watch "Inception" again, frankly because I could never really figure out the last part of the movie. Following the movie, had a wonderful dinner(courtesy of my mother) and went to bed. Now, I'm lying on the bed, listening to the tick-tocks of that wretched clock of mine, and I don't know when I slip into a reverie of dreams. Now this is where things start to get weird..... I am sitting with my laptop, doing something(which I don't distinctly remember)...... I check my clock.... its 3pm.... My dad comes into my room.... DAD: Has the guy from the AC service centre come yet? ME: Is he supposed to? Well not yet, he hasn't..... My dad leaves..... feeling tired.... I decide to take a power-nap :P I wake up and find myself at a corridor in our school, Frank Anthony Public School.... weird... but no one is around.... weirder...... I find myself taking the stairs to the roof. I'm on the roof, and wow what a beautiful weather... clear sky with a bright sun... Suddenly a cloaked figure appears infront of me.... he turns around.... hey I know this guy, its my friend LazyBlogger HIM: Dude, I'm not who you think I am. Duh!!!... what?.. wait a minute I know this guy for the past 4 years and why does he sound like Marlon Brando...?????.... HIM (with a weird grin on his face): I am a CIA agent, and you have something that belongs to me... CIA...nah... he a tech-wiz no doubt, but CIA... and what do I have that belongs to him??? ME: I do? HIM (taking out a gun from under that long dark cloak): You don't remember? ME: Is that a real gun? (I can be a real ass sometimes even in my dreams :P) HIM: Give me my CD or you're history. ME: What CD? ...and thats when it clicked... ME: You mean the Ubuntu 10.10 CD? But I don't have it here, will give it to you tomorrow in college.... HIM: Check the left pocket of your jacket... ....what jacket? I wasn't wearig any jacket.... well it so happened I was wearing one... and out of the left pocket came the Ubuntu 10.10 CD phew!!!!... I'm saved... I hand it over to him... HIM: Well goodbye then... ..his gun still pointing at me..... ME: Why? HIM: Because now you know I'm CIA. ME: Wait a minute.... I won't tell anyone... please... HIM: That's what the all say..... BANG!!!!... BANG!!!!! I sit up with a jolt..... on my bed... my laptop still open on my working table..... The bell rings...I hear someone opening the door...I hear my dad calling out to me DAD: The AC service man has come, could you see to it that he does the job properly, I'm going out... ME: Okay ....phew it was dream...... I get up....and suddenly a loud monotonous ringing sound..... I reach out and stop the alarm of my table clock right beside my bed... I'm lying on my bed.... Its 6:30 in the morning today And I realized I had had a dream inside a dream.... neat :D .... a first for me... well atleast the first I remember atleast.. Another weird day(or night) In my Life. :P

item.title: CMS Demistifyed - Wordpress vs Drupal vs Joomla
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded: [box type="info"]A content management system (CMS) is the collection of tools used to manage, store, retrieve data for an individual or enterprise.[/box] It often becomes a necessity when we have to choose between a CMS for our needs. Although there are a number of CMS available out there, we will primarily focus our discussion here to Wordpress, Joomla and Drupal. All three of these are open-CMS type, each having its own advantages and disadvantages. [button link="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_content_management_systems" type="icon" color="silver" icon="paper"]NOTE: You may browse through a list of CMS here[/button] The best way to understand the relative advantages and disadvantages of the three CMS is by chalking out the differences as follows: [tabs slidertype="left tabs"][tabcontainer] [tabtext]Reliability[/tabtext] [tabtext]Security[/tabtext] [tabtext]Extendability[/tabtext] [/tabcontainer] [tabcontent] [tab]I have to say that all three systems are all very reliable. Ive been using WordPress for the longest period of time, Drupal for a while, and Joomla for the least amount of time. WordPress - WordPress has always lived up to its name no matter what type of website its running. But when it comes to reliability with WordPress, I would have to say it would be the highest out of all three of these systems. Ive been using WordPress for quite some time now, and I have to say, Ive really gotten to know the interface and how the community works with it. Because the community for WordPress is quite large, bugs, updates, or even suggestions are handled at the highest priority because it is in fact one of the largest open source blogging (even though it can be used for much more than just blogging) systems out there. Joomla - I have to say Joomla is one of the least reliable systems out there. It can be very sluggish at times and it was also quite glitchy at certain times also. To get Joomla to do some things what the other two systems can do requires some third party plugins, which in the end of it, adds more room for error because of being third party and some of them being in very early stages of development, which many plugins are. Drupal - Drupal has to be one of my favorite systems out there. Its great for blogging, running an e-commerce website, or even using it for your product page of your latest application. Drupals reliability is very high compared to Joomla (atleast in my opinion), but Im not sure if I would say its any better or worse than WordPress. Drupal is a very stable system and Ive never had any major problems with it before. [/tab] [tab]All three systems are fairly secure, but theres one system in here thats very prone to security issues. WordPress - WordPress has had its security issues before, but as of right now, the security issues are very tight in WordPress and if there is any security issues, its typically caused by WordPresss third party plugins. Joomla - Okay, Im not the person to ask about security issues in Joomla, but, I have to say, Joomla is the worst CMS program Ive ever used when it comes to security. Drupal - For the most part, Drupal is very secure. There were some major security issues in the past but up till recently, I cannot say theres really anything in regards to security issues. Drupal powers some pretty hefty sites and its why some people prefer it as the CMS as choice for some very major websites. [/tab] [tab]I believe the most important feature of any CMS is extendability. When we say extendability, were talking about themes, plugins, and everything in that nature. WordPress - Without a doubt I would have to say WordPress has the most extendability out of any CMS system. WordPress has a vast amount of themes ranging from free to paid, many plugins to extend WordPress to do anything you want, and also the basic system of managing plugins overall is very easy to use (especially in WordPress 3.0). Whether you want to add, delete, or even modify an existing plugin, its very easy to do in WordPress. Moreover creating themes for Wordpress is probably the easiest among the three. Joomla - For any Joomla user, it comes with a good amount of plugins, or which are called extensions in Joomla, but some plugins are a bit lazily made or they just dont work correctly all the time. In other words, there are quite a few plugins that you want to avoid in Joomla. Also, compared to the out-of-the-box extendability, Joomla doesnt have as near the amount of features than other CMS systems. It doesnt even have a native comment system. Granted, Joomla isnt entirely meant for a blog, but a good portion of users use it for that reason. For theming support, Joomla comes with a good amount of themes and some websites even dedicated for Joomla themes. Drupal - I have to say Drupals plugins are fairly nice and its very easy to write one on your own, but I see some plugins, or what Drupal calls modules, that are a bit neglected. Finding themes for Drupal can be a bit harder because theres not as much as WordPress, but you can typically find a theme thatll fit your needs/wants. And as a developer, I finding theming Drupal to be rather easy. [/tab] [/tabcontent] [/tabs] So, the final question is which is better. The answer is simple really, each has a different area where each excels. I my opinion, if you want a blog , go for Wordpress. If your need is an e-commerce site, choose Drupal or Joomla. If your requirement is a static site, then choose either of these (though personally I would go for Wordpress). Wordpress is probably the most used and liked of all the CMS. Drupal represents an 'advanced' CMS for users who really know the stuff. And Joomla, requires a little bit more to do.

item.title: Self-Described Mac vs. PC People
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded:
Profile of a Self-Described Mac Person vs. PC Person is a fun infographic looking at personality and preference differences.  Based on 388,315 survey respondents from Hunch.com, it illustrates topics like who throws parties, math aptitude, taste in art, cocktail drinks of choice and would they ride a Vespa or a Harley.

Our latest data project was to analyze how self-described Mac and PC people are different. The infographic below, designed by the talented folks at Column Five Media, breaks it down.

Back in ye olden days of Hunch — November 2009 — we explored the differences in personality, aesthetic tastes, and media preferences between Mac and PC users. Since then, the Hunch user base and question pool have grown many times over. The 2009 report started with more than 76,000 responses to its base “Mac or PC?” question. The same question now has nearly 400,000 responses. This is all in the context of the more than 80 million “Teach Hunch About You” questions which have been answered on Hunch to date.

Very funny, and a great job by the design team at Column Five Media!  Found on FlowingData and Visual News

item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded:
Thought I would dedicate this post to our Indepence Day.... Here's what others are saying.... Finally a small piece of information:
Do you know that Jana Gana Mana is a five-stanza Brahmo hymn composed and scored in a highly Sanskritized Bengali by Rabindranath Tagore. The first stanza of the song has been adopted as the National Anthem of India.
Anyways here is the entire song... item.title: The Wait
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded: Well this post is kind of a personal note rather than an informative piece of text. If you know mw well, you probably know that I got my offer letter from Tata Consultancy Services in January of this year, as I had mentioned in a previous post. But that was rather easy compared to the last eight months waiting patiently for the "YET TO BE BATCHED" to change into a valid date and place. The wait became more frustrating perhaps because close friends were leaving for their companies and some had already started work. And then there are the nosy neighbours and weird relatives, who never fail to point out, "Kire ekhono aseni?" or "kobe jachchis training'e?" and a number of other such questions. The pressure builds to a point, when you start to doubt your memory of actually clearing the interview and accepting the offer letter. The last few months I tried reading, giving tutions, watching some stupid movies which I didn't even like and "playing dead" on my bed. But quite frankly nothing helped. The news of other colleges receiving their joining letters didn't help much either. So anyways long story(of frustrating wait) short received my joining letter on the 14th September night. As written the training will be in Kolkata, but will commence from 28th march 2012 :(. I'm part relieved because, now atleast there is something to look forward to, but the again another wait for 6 months... Life's such a pain in the ass, I tell you. P.S.: What a waste of cyberspace right? :P

item.title: POST JSON data in PHP
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded: I was working with PHP the other day and had to send JSON data, and got stuck at a problem: How to send a POST request from PHP with correct-formatted JSON data? Now you can't send post fields, because you want to send JSON. So the solution? Well the solution is like this: 1. We create the correct JSON data 2. Set that as the body of the POST request 3. Set the headers correctly so that the server understands what we sent Here's how we do it: [php] $data = array("first_name" => "Suplab", "last_name" => "Debnath"); $data_string = json_encode($data); $ch = curl_init('http://api.local/rest/users'); curl_setopt($ch, CURLOPT_CUSTOMREQUEST, "POST"); curl_setopt($ch, CURLOPT_POSTFIELDS, $data_string); curl_setopt($ch, CURLOPT_RETURNTRANSFER, true); curl_setopt($ch, CURLOPT_HTTPHEADER, array( 'Content-Type: application/json', 'Content-Length: ' . strlen($data_string)) ); $result = curl_exec($ch); [/php] To understand curl_setopt() better you can visit here. What we are trying to do is make a POST request, but the body of the request is set to the json-encoded data, and the setting the proper headers to describe the request body. The CURLOPT_RETURNTRANSFER is used so that the response from the server gets thrown into $result rather than get echoed.

Through which I travel,

Invading

Thrust in this void chasm which,
I can neither cross nor fathom.
I swim solitary
Seeking a ray of hope
That only your touch can provide.

item.title: A guide to flashing Poseidon ROM on Galaxy SL i9003
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded:
This post is a step by step guide to setting up Blaqkarma's Poseidon ROM on your Galaxy SL GT-i9003 phone. Go through the entire tutorial before commencing.
Requisites:
  • XXKPE
  • XXKPQ/XXKPU
  • CF-Root/Ultra Chaos Kernel v15
  • Poseidon Rom
  • Odin v1.85
Note:
  • The process involves flashing XXKPE followed by flashing XXKPQ or XXKPU. Both processes are explained below.
  • XXKPE will convert any file system you have to rfs.
  • XXKPU/XXKPQ and XXKPE both need to be extracted to some desired location.
  • CF-Root and Poseidon ROM need not be extracted.
  • Put the Poseidon zipped file in your external SD card.
  • Wipe cache and factory reset by going to recovery mode (Home button + Volume Up + Power button) after flashing each XXKPE, XXKPU/XXKPQ, CF-Root and Poseidon otherwise you may face random reboots automatically.
  • You might want to give UC kernel a try for extra tweaks and improving the performance.
Set-Up before starting:
  1. Make sure the phone drivers are installed on your PC and Kies is not running.
  2. Backup your apps and any important data.
  3. Take a backup of contacts, by go to Contacts -> Menu -> Import/Export.
  4. Take a backup of SMS via SMS Backup and Restore by Ritesh Sahu.
  5. Copy contact generated vsf file and sms backup file to your PC or laptop.
  6. Keep the usb cable at hand before starting.
  7. Make sure your phone has more than 60% battery.
  8. Switch Off your mobile.
Process:


Re-partitioning
  1. Put your mobile in Downloading mode by Pressing Volume Down key + the Home key and holding them press the Power button.
  2. Now Start ODIN.
  3. Connect Mobile To Computer, you will see the ID:COM port light up in ODIN with port number on which your phone is connected.
  4. Now click on PIT button and select latona_20110114.pit and check the Re-partition below the ID:COM and click on Start button.
  5. It will show a blank screen once its flashed, now disconnect the phone from computer and remove your mobile battery and put it back.
Flashing with XXKPE
  1. Put your mobile in Downloading mode by Pressing Volume Down key + the Home key and holding them press the Power button.
  2. Now Start ODIN.
  3. Connect Mobile To Computer, you will see the ID:COM port light up in ODIN with port number on which your phone is connected.
  4. Make sure the repartition box is unchecked.
  5. Now click on BOOT LOADER and select the APBOOT_I9003XXKPE_CL409735_REV08_user_low_ship.tar.md5 file.
  6. Click on PDA and select the CODE_I9003XXKPE_CL409735_REV08_user_low_ship.tar.md5.
  7. Click on PHONE and select the MODEM_I9003XXKPE_REV_00_CL1041909.tar.md5.
  8. Click on CSC and select the GT-I9003-CSC-MULTI-OXAKPE.tar.md.
  9. Now click on Start.
  10. Wait for process to complete and do not detach phone from PC until it finishes successfully and you see PASS with green color.
  11. The phone will boot and your firmware now would be 2.3.4 XXKPE.
  12. Turn off the phone.
Flashing with XXKPQ
Flash mobile again with XXKPE. When using XXKPQ it is crucial that you flash XXKPE twice. After flashing with XXKPE twice,
  1. Put your mobile in Downloading mode by Pressing Volume Down key + the Home key and holding them Power button.
  2. Now connect your phone to computer, in ODIN, ID:COM box will turn into yellow.
  3. Click on PDA and select I9003XXKPQ_I9003XXKPQ_I9003SERKPQ_HOME.tar.md5.
  4. Click on start button.
  5. Wait for process to complete and do not detach phone from PC until it finishes successfully and you see PASS with green color.
  6. The phone will boot and your firmware now would be 2.3.6 XXKPQ.
  7. Turn off the phone.
Flashing with XXKPU
Skip this if you are using XXKPQ
  1. Put your mobile in Downloading mode by Pressing Volume Down key + the Home key and holding them Power button.
  2. Now connect your phone to computer, in ODIN, ID:COM box will turn into yellow.
  3. Click on PDA and select I9003XXKPU_I9003XXKPU_I9003SERKPU_HOME.tar.md5.
  4. Click on start button.
  5. Wait for process to complete and do not detach phone from PC until it finishes successfully and you see PASS with green color.
  6. The phone will boot and your firmware now would be 2.3.6 XXKPU.
  7. Switch off the phone.
Flashing Root
  1. Put your mobile in Downloading mode by Pressing Volume Down key + the Home key and holding them Press the Power button.
  2. Connect you mobile to computer, now click on PDA in ODIN and go to folder where you have downloaded the CF-Root/UC Kernel v15.
  3. Click on start and wait till process got completed.
Flashing the Poseidon ROM
  1. Copy Poseidon file in your external sdcard POSEIDONS_ROM_XXKPQ_01-09-12.zip.
  2. Switch of your phone and start in recovery mode by Pressing Volume UP key + the Home key and holding them press the Power button.
  3. It will start in CWM recovery mode. Click on install zip from sdcard and just flash the Poseidon zip.
  4. Your phone will auto restart. If not then select reboot phone.
Enjoy Poseidon on your phone!!!
NOTE: I am not responsible for any damage, that might happen during the flashing process or any accidental bricking of your phone....

item.title: Of Ruins and Runes
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded: This week made a quick trip to Murshidabad, the former capital of undivided Bengal during the time of the Nawabs. The city with its narrow alleys, broken fragile palaces and mosques, tangas and innumerable graves of royalties is a testament to the ages of the Nawabs.
